317","1316–1386":"van9januari1316to8januari1317–1386","1316":"van 9 januari 1316 to 8 januari 1317","1386":"1386","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1317":"1317","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1292–1317":"1292–1317","1295–1316":"1295–from9January1316to8January1317","1316–1386":"from9January1316to8January1317–1386","1316":"from 9 January 1316 to 8 January 1317","1386":"1386","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1317":"1317","England":"England, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mnu","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Chi Wing, Ming, Kin, Ping, Siu Wah, Sung, Wai Lin, Yim, Yung, Bung, Hung, Tu.  Romanian Nicolae.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 苗 and 繆, see   Miao   1 and 2.","Romanian: from an altered form of <i>Mihu</i>, a pet form of the personal name   Mihai  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Miao","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Wei, Lan, Li, Ping, Tao, Xue, Chang, Chun Mei, Dong Sheng, Feng Ying, Gang, Guo Jun, Hai, Haiping, Han Yong, Min, Xuan, Yen, You.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 苗, meaning ‘seedling’ in Chinese: (i) from the placename Miao (苗), the name of a fief (located in Jiyuan in Henan province) granted to Ben Huang, who fled to the state of Jin after his father Bo Fen, an official in the state of Chu, was murdered during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) a surname from the state of Bai Ji (located in the Korean peninsula)."]}]},{"name":"Trivett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Trevett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trevett","meanings":["English (Dorset): apparently from Middle English <i>trivet</i>, <i>trevet</i> ‘trivet, tripod’ (Old English <i>trefet</i>), especially for a three-footed stand for a pot, kettle, or pan placed over a fire during cooking or heating. In Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, and the North Midlands this name has become confused with   Trewhitt  ."]},{"name":"Trivette","meanings":["English: altered form of   Trivett  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Mnu Trivett was born in 1292, in Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Henry Trivett. She died in 1317, in her hometown, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1292–1317":"1292–1317","1295–1316":"1295–9.jaanuar1316kuni8.jaanuar1317","1316–1386":"9.jaanuar1316kuni8.jaanuar1317–1386","1316":"9. jaanuar 1316 kuni 8. jaanuar 1317","1386":"1386","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1317":"1317","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1292–1317":"1292–1317","1295–1316":"1295–vuodesta9.tammikuuta1316vuoteen8.tammikuuta1317","1316–1386":"vuodesta9.tammikuuta1316vuoteen8.tammikuuta1317–1386","1316":"vuodesta 9. tammikuuta 1316 vuoteen 8. tammikuuta 1317","1386":"1386","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1317":"1317","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1292–1317":"1292–1317","1295–1316":"1295–du9janvier1316au8janvier1317","1316–1386":"du9janvier1316au8janvier1317–1386","1316":"du 9 janvier 1316 au 8 janvier 1317","1386":"1386","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1317":"1317","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Joan Mnu Trivett est née en 1292, à Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Henry Trivett. Elle est décédée en 1317, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 25 ans."},"de":{"1292–1317":"1292–1317","1295–1316":"1295–von9.Januar1316bis8.Januar1317","1316–1386":"von9.Januar1316bis8.Januar1317–1386","1316":"von 9. Januar 1316 bis 8. Januar 1317","1386":"1386","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1317":"1317","England":"England, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Schottland, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Joan Mnu Trivett wurde 1292 in Schottland,